<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a transformer turns ratio?", answer: "The turns ratio of a transformer is the ratio of the number of turns in the primary winding to the number in the secondary winding: N1/N2. This ratio determines the voltage transformation: V1/V2 = N1/N2. A turns ratio greater than 1 means the transformer is a step-down type (lower output voltage), while less than 1 means step-up (higher output voltage). A 1:1 ratio is an isolation transformer that provides electrical isolation without changing voltage." },
  { question: "How does a transformer change voltage?", answer: "A transformer changes voltage through electromagnetic induction. Alternating current in the primary winding creates a changing magnetic field in the core, which induces a voltage in the secondary winding. The voltage ratio equals the turns ratio: V2 = V1 * (N2/N1). For an ideal transformer, power is conserved: V1*I1 = V2*I2, so stepping up voltage proportionally steps down current and vice versa. Real transformers have efficiency losses of 2-10% due to resistance, core losses, and flux leakage." },
  { question: "What is the difference between step-up and step-down transformers?", answer: "A step-up transformer has more secondary turns than primary turns (N2 > N1), producing a higher output voltage and lower output current. A step-down transformer has fewer secondary turns (N2 < N1), producing lower voltage and higher current. Power transmission uses step-up transformers at generating stations (to reduce line losses) and step-down transformers near consumers (to provide safe voltages). The transformer on a utility pole is typically a step-down unit converting thousands of volts to 120/240V." },
  { question: "What is transformer efficiency?", answer: "Transformer efficiency is the ratio of output power to input power, expressed as a percentage. Ideal transformers are 100% efficient (V1*I1 = V2*I2), but real transformers have losses from copper resistance (I^2R heating in windings), core losses (hysteresis and eddy currents in the iron core), and flux leakage. High-quality power transformers achieve 95-99% efficiency. Distribution transformers typically operate at 97-99% efficiency. Small electronic transformers may be 85-95% efficient." },
  { question: "Why can't transformers work with DC?", answer: "Transformers require a changing magnetic field to induce voltage in the secondary winding. Direct current creates a constant magnetic field that does not change with time, so no voltage is induced after the initial transient. If DC is applied continuously, only the primary winding resistance limits the current, which can overheat and destroy the transformer. To use transformers with DC sources, the DC must first be converted to AC using an inverter, which is exactly how switch-mode power supplies and DC-DC converters work." }
]) %>

